I"Â<p>Designed circuit with five input controls (switches and pushbuttons), three LEDs, fiber optics, buzzer, and fan. Developed three stages using digital electronics: logic gates, one shot, shift register, demultiplexer, counter, and SR latch. <!--more--> Simulated circuit in MultiSim. Tested on breadboard. Soldered and packaged final product. Utilized feedback and sequential logic to ensure stages must be unlocked in order. Forced stage reset upon incorrect timing or sequence. Indicated stage completion with LEDs.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/lock-box-power-supply-e1421090287790.jpg" alt="lock box + power supply" height="300px" /></p>

<h4 id="circuitry-design">Circuitry Design</h4>

<p>When trying to simulate the lock in MultiSim, I realized that the push-button was way too short of a pulse to be used as it was designed in the working design. Additionally, I didn‚Äôt realize how huge the timing delay is on MultiSim, but eventually I figured it out. (Hence the 20Hz YOCLK pulse‚Ä¶I plan on actually using an ~1Hz YOCLK. I‚Äôm also going to change the timing delay of the One Shots to ~0.5 sec.) The way the lock is shown, the final LED does not turn off unless the power is turned off, but I am going to try to rework that portion as well as trying to remove a logic gate in the first stage.</p>

